   <indicator ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Output Indicator</narrative>
    </title>
    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">National Climate Change Learning Strategy in place.</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2015">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">In line with Article 6 of the UNFCCC, the National Climate Change Policy recognizes that good communication, education and awareness-raising around climate change are all essential to deliver its objectives. However, Ghana does not have a comprehensive strategy on climate learning.</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2019-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2019-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Situation analysis to assess climate change knowledge among school children, teachers and opinion leaders
2. Climate change and green economy integrated in school curricula</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. In order to effectively integrate climate change and green economy into school educational curricula, a comprehensive assessment of knowledge levels of teachers and school children was conducted to serve as background information for evidence-based decision making.

2. Teaching and Learning Materials (TLMs) were developed to have a standard set of peer-reviewed high-quality materials to support teaching and learning of climate change and green economy in Ghana.To ensure full implementation of the revised school curricula, the EPA in collaboration with Ghana Education Service agreed to undertake training of trainers programme in 12 regions as part of the efforts to transform the education sector and make it more relevant to meet the currently changing trends of climate, its impact on human resource, as well as green development needs of Ghana. In each region, fifty primary school teachers were trained on climate change &amp; green economy indicators of the new syllabus including involving 70% public schools, 20% private schools and 10% administrators (Directors &amp; Supervisor) in each of the regions.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
   </indicator>
